The sentence "Les années sauterelles de l'Amérique Latine" translates to "The locust years of Latin America" in English.
The bad news continues to accumulate in Latin America these days.
Economic conditions are worsening almost everywhere, social cohesion is diminishing, and political instability is growing.
It is not surprising given that the majority of Latin American countries have gone nowhere over the last twenty years.
The capital was sold off and national debts disproportionately increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial was achieved.
These years have really been devoured by the locusts.
Over the last 20 years, the annual growth rate of per capita GDP in Latin America has reached an average of 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in world trade except through a modest increase in wages?
Economic stagnation is a result of poor government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors placed her on this path.
Firstly, in the rush towards privatization, everything from public services to processing industries was put up for auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues derived from privatization have produced little in terms of improved infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by a massive external borrowing.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the loan taken out by national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not reached the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring prosperity, the region became disillusioned.
The influx of capital produced an effect of wealth, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing in, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would push the patience of middle-class Latin Americans beyond the limits of political survival.
But without a larger number of deeper reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
The development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that functioned according to technocratic lines and considered economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents keep succeeding one after another.
The institutions are being brought down, property rights are being questioned, and an even more corrupt random redistribution effort is on the way.
Peru and Venezuela are not much luckier; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls in the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large portion of Latin American populations is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic thinking and politics that capital has already begun to flee - even though the elections are still several months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought about greater stability, but this could prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks landing hard.
Regarding all the good news about Mexico's nascent democracy, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it has to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economically reasoned financial result because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and thus little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now yearns for the fat 1970s OPEC years -- in which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The richness of Argentina is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that sold their assets and borrowed instead of saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Here is the English translation of the given French sentence:  "Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt."
The government institutions favor the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
The rewards for taking risks and showing initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.   Note: The translation assumes "pauvre" here means economically poor or less developed, as context can sometimes shift the meaning of "pauvre" in French. If you meant poverty in the sense of lack of resources, it might be better translated as "poor" without specifying "economically."
The per capita PNB represents only half of that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region of around 15% annually, who can seriously doubt that within the next 15 years it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, primarily due to the massive flow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to deteriorate: governments are reversing reforms and the economy is falling behind the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when untapped funds were flowing in, but these times are largely over.
We therefore have to expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem — another presidential candidate from Argentina once again — may appear to be a bad joke, but anyone concerned about the future of Latin America should not laugh at them.
